<!-- WRITTEN GUIDE -->
<section class="section" id="written">
  <div class="page-wrap">
    <div class="section-header fade-up">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Step 3 — Reference Guide</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Written User Guide</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Detailed step-by-step instructions for every feature. Bookmark this page for quick reference.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-wrap fade-up">
      <div class="guide-nav">
        <div class="guide-tab active" onclick="switchTab('dashboard')">Dashboard</div>
        <div class="guide-tab" onclick="switchTab('inventory')">Inventory</div>
        <div class="guide-tab" onclick="switchTab('pos')">Sales & POS</div>
        <div class="guide-tab" onclick="switchTab('suppliers')">Suppliers</div>
        <div class="guide-tab" onclick="switchTab('analytics')">Analytics</div>
        <div class="guide-tab" onclick="switchTab('security')">Security</div>
        <div class="guide-tab" onclick="switchTab('sync')">Cloud Sync</div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-body">

        <div class="guide-panel active" id="panel-dashboard">
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Understanding the Dashboard</div>
              <div class="step-desc">The Dashboard is your store's command center. The four metric cards at the top show your Total Inventory Value (all products × their prices), Total Products in your catalog, Low Stock Alerts (products at or below minimum stock), and Today's Sales (all transactions completed today).</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Sales Overview Chart</div>
              <div class="step-desc">The line chart shows your sales for the last 7 days. It updates automatically every time a sale is completed. If you've just started, most days will show $0 — that's normal.</div>
              <div class="tip-box">💡 The chart pulls from real transaction data. To see activity, complete a few test sales in Sales & POS.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Stock Alerts Panel</div>
              <div class="step-desc">This panel lists every product whose current stock is at or below its Minimum Stock setting. Click the Inventory section to manage these products and reorder from suppliers.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-panel" id="panel-inventory">
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Adding a New Product</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Click <strong>Add Product</strong> (top right or in the Inventory toolbar). Fill in the Product Name, Category, Price, Cost, Stock Quantity, and Minimum Stock. The Minimum Stock value is the threshold that triggers a low-stock alert on the dashboard.</div>
              <div class="tip-box">💡 The <strong>Cost</strong> field is used to calculate your Gross Margin in Analytics. It's not shown to customers — it's for your records only.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Editing a Product</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Click <strong>Edit</strong> on any product card. Change any field and click <strong>Save Product</strong>. Stock levels, prices, and supplier assignments can all be updated this way.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Searching and Filtering</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Use the search bar to find products by name or barcode. Use the category dropdown to filter by product type. Both filters work together — you can search "milk" within "Dairy" only.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">4</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Deleting a Product</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Click <strong>Delete</strong> on any product card. A confirmation prompt will appear. Deleted products cannot be recovered unless you have a backup — consider reducing stock to 0 instead if you may want it back.</div>
              <div class="warn-box">⚠️ Deletion is permanent. Export your data first if you're unsure.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-panel" id="panel-pos">
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Adding Products to Cart</div>
              <div class="step-desc">In Sales & POS, type a product name or scan a barcode into the search bar. The matching product is added to the cart automatically. You can also click <strong>Add to Cart</strong> from the Inventory section.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Adjusting Quantities</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Use the <kbd>+</kbd> and <kbd>-</kbd> buttons next to each cart item to change quantity. Click <kbd>×</kbd> to remove an item entirely. The subtotal, tax, and total update in real time.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Processing a Payment</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Click <strong>Process Payment</strong>. Select Cash or Card, optionally enter the customer's name, then click <strong>Complete Payment</strong>. Stock levels update automatically and the transaction appears in Recent Transactions.</div>
              <div class="tip-box">💡 Tax is calculated automatically based on your Tax Rate setting in Settings → Store Settings.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-panel" id="panel-suppliers">
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Adding a Supplier</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Go to Suppliers and click <strong>Add Supplier</strong>. Enter the supplier's name, phone number, and email address. Once saved, the supplier appears as an option when adding or editing products.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Linking Suppliers to Products</div>
              <div class="step-desc">When adding or editing a product, choose the supplier from the dropdown. This links the product to a supplier so you can quickly identify where to reorder from when stock runs low.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-panel" id="panel-analytics">
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Sales Trends Chart</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Shows total sales per week for the past 4 weeks. Use this to spot your busiest periods and plan stock accordingly.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Top Products Chart</div>
              <div class="step-desc">A doughnut chart showing the 5 most-sold products by quantity. Products with no sales show a placeholder value of 1 so the chart renders correctly.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Performance Metrics</div>
              <div class="step-desc"><strong>Gross Margin</strong> is (Revenue − Cost) ÷ Revenue across your whole inventory. <strong>Inventory Turnover</strong> is units sold ÷ average stock. <strong>Avg. Transaction</strong> is the mean sale value. <strong>Stock Accuracy</strong> is the % of products above minimum stock level.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-panel" id="panel-security">
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Your PIN protects everything</div>
              <div class="step-desc">When you first open StoreWise, you create a 4–6 digit PIN. This PIN is the key that encrypts all your data using AES-256-GCM — an industry-standard encryption algorithm. Your PIN is never stored — only a salted hash is kept for verification.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Auto-lock</div>
              <div class="step-desc">The app automatically locks after 15 minutes of inactivity. You can also lock it manually at any time using the <strong>🔒 Lock App</strong> button in the sidebar footer.</div>
              <div class="tip-box">💡 Always lock the app when stepping away from a shared device.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Changing your PIN</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Go to Settings → Security → Change PIN. You'll need your current PIN. All data is automatically re-encrypted with the new PIN.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">4</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Forgot your PIN?</div>
              <div class="step-desc">On the lock screen, tap <em>Forgot PIN? Reset all data</em>. This permanently deletes all encrypted data and resets the app. This is why cloud sync and regular exports are important — they're your backup.</div>
              <div class="warn-box">⚠️ There is no way to recover data without the PIN. The encryption is designed so that not even the app developers can access your data.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="guide-panel" id="panel-sync">
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Local File (simplest)</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Go to Settings → Data Sync → Local File and click <strong>Choose / Create File</strong>. Pick where to save your data on your computer. The app auto-saves an encrypted <code>.enc</code> file every time data changes. Works in Chrome and Edge only.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Google Drive</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Click <strong>Connect Google Drive</strong> and sign in with your Google account. An encrypted file called <code>storewise-data.enc</code> is created in your Drive. Google cannot read the contents — only you can, with your PIN.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Dropbox</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Click <strong>Connect Dropbox</strong> and sign in. Works the same way as Google Drive — an encrypted file is saved to your Dropbox root folder.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-step">
            <div class="step-num">4</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Manual Export/Import</div>
              <div class="step-desc">Settings → Backup → Export All Data downloads a plain JSON file. This is a readable backup — useful for migrating data or as an emergency backup. Keep this file in a secure location.</div>
              <div class="warn-box">⚠️ Exported JSON files are <strong>not encrypted</strong>. Don't store them in shared folders.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

